'''Flitterjigs''' is a description of an item of clothing that is in 'tatters' or 'ribbons'. This word has its origins in the [[19th century]] English spoken in county [[Donegal]] in north west of [[Ireland]] where the local people are reckoned to possess the largest lexicon of both [[English language|English]] and [[Gaelic language|Gaelic]] in Ireland. Unused for over a century, the word experienced a renaissance in the early [[1990s]] when it was seized upon by a group of middle class [[Dublin]]ers and a rogue Clareman and subsequently used as an endearing icon of their rapidly fading heritage.

SOURCE:
Traynor, Michael, 1953. The English Dialect of Donegal, A Glossary, Incorporating the Collections of H. C. Hart, M.R.I.A. (1847-1980), Dublin: The Royal Irish Academy.


